Concrete curing, is actually an EXOTHERMIC reaction.  Curing concrete causes a small amount of heat energy to be released by the curing reaction, due to chemical reactions between the water and the soda ash/slaked lime/etc.  When you heated it up, it increased the temperature, increasing the rate at which this reaction occurred slightly and evaporated the water out too quickly.  Result...  not enough   time   for the crystalline bonds to form into nice large crystals.  You can mix concrete for it to have a quick settning bond that will cure in mere moments...  but it will be WEAK, because larger crystals, which are stronger, take a long time to form and harden.  When it cures too quickly, those crystals form, but are much smaller and do not bond together as well, thus, weaker concrete.
